Tom, I have added you as a cc on this ticket. Story so far:
- Zara raised an issue several months ago with image editing in sports pages;
- We spent some time looking at it but could not find a satisfactory resolution;
- Zara asked us to come up with a time estimate for solving the issue, which we did not do after which the issue got parked;
- Last month, we spotted the ticket and updated it with a couple of suggestions for workarounds;
- This month I brazenly attempted to close the ticket with the inevitable response from Liz.

It would be very helpful if you could give us some guidance on how high a priority addressing this issue is likely to be and how you would like us to proceed.

In particular, is this issue currently a problem for CMS users; are you expecting a larger number of people to be accessing the CMS without access to Firefox over the next 10 months or so; and is the suggestion of refactoring the page likely to be a solution that you are interested in?

Many thanks.

Hi Andy,
It's slightly more complicated than just providing 3 reports, as there are quite a few scenarios.
Please see the attached report (password as before) observing the following key:

"NF" means that we did NOT find a match. 

"X1" means that we found the path, after making a number of fixed substitutions for some common "bad" inbound links (as follows, in php)
     // $p is the requested path. 		
     $p = preg_replace('/^\/games\/venues\/games\//', "/games/", $p);
     $p = preg_replace('/^\/about\//', "/about-us/", $p);
     $p = preg_replace('/^(\/games\/olympic-sports){2}/', "/games/olympic-sports", $p);
     $p = preg_replace('/^\/sports\/olympic\//', "/games/olympic-sports/", $p);
     $p = preg_replace('/^\/sports\//', "/games/", $p);
     $p = preg_replace('/^\/about-this-website\/about-this-website\//', "/about-this-website/", $p);
     $p = preg_replace('/^\/about-this-website\/get-involved\//', "/get-involved/", $p);
     $p = preg_replace('/^\/games\/olympic-sport-competition-schedule\/index\.php/', "/games/sport-competition-schedules/olympic-sport-competition-schedule.php", $p);
     $p = preg_replace('/^\/blog\/includes(\/blog\/.*)/', '$1', $p);

"X2" is special case concerning errant inbound links to /about-this-website/.

"Hn" means that we found the path after performing "n" hops back up the directory structure.

"Yn" is the special case where we performed "n" hops back up the directory structure, arrived at /news/index.php, and then looked in /news/bid-phase.
Another way of looking at this is that it means that /news/path/to/file.php was NOT found but that /news/bid-phase/path/to/file.php WAS found.


Please let me know if you have any questions.

Kieran
